# Game commentary source.

# Formatting:
# [*LINK]: Jump to a new note; also display source if possible. (Default behavior.)
# [~LINK]: Display source for LINK, but keep this note open.
# [text|*LINK], [text|~LINK]: Specify link text.
# [text|https://...] External link.

ABOUT: Welcome to the commentary track!

rtn:V-VERSION: Print the title, release, and serial number.
	In 1982, Infocom briefly branded its games as “INTERLOGIC”. They had mostly switched to “interactive fiction” by 1984.

GRAMMAR-LEGEND: This is the list of verb forms which the game recognizes. (Simple directions like `NORTH` are a special case; they’re not listed here.) These are compiled from the [SYNTAX|~src:SYNTAX-58] file.
	Objects in a verb line have various flags which give hints about their usage. An object attribute (like `LIGHTBIT`) means that if the player doesn’t name an object, the parser will try to guess one with that attribute.
	The other flag letters have specific meanings: **m**ultiple objects are accepted; the player must **h**ave the object; the player will automatically **t**ake the object; the object should be **i**n the room or **o**n the ground; the object should be **p**ossessed or **c**arried in a container. (Yes, they’re confusing. Infocom’s own docs say “No one really understands them except Stu” (Galley).)

attr:RMUNGBIT: Not applied to real objects. `RMUNGBIT` is a hack used in grammar lines; it means the object is optional (but the preposition before it is required). This allows the parser to accept commands like [LOOK AROUND|~src:SYNTAX-218].

glob:P-SYNTAX: The grammar line found when the most recent command was parsed. (Except for simple direction commands, which are a special case.) See the Grammar tab.


OBJTREE-LEGEND: In this list, `Rooms` are rooms and `Items` are regular items. (Sometimes portable, sometimes not.)
	`Scen` indicates scenery objects. These exist in multiple places; for example, the [~obj:PLANTERS] are visible in most of the colored hallways.
	`Glob` indicates a global object, which is *always* visible, or at least mentionable. For example, [~obj:GRUE] is global – not because grues are always present, but so you can always ask `WHAT IS A GRUE`.

obj:LOCAL-GLOBALS: This is a container for scenery objects like [~obj:PLANTERS], which are visible from many locations in the game.


src:DUNGEON-19: This refers to the word `MGCKJK` in [~obj:LOCAL-GLOBALS], above.
	Why is this synonym necessary? Not clear! Most Infocom games have it (or a variation), but some say “No, this synonym doesn’t need to exist” instead.
	If you type `EXAMINE MGCKJK`, the parser finds [~obj:local-globals]. But that object is nameless, so you get a garbage reply. Go on, try it.

obj:ADVENTURER: Yes, the player’s printed name is “cretin”, although the game never says so. This sort of sarcastic insult hasn’t aged too well, but MIT culture had a lot of it. Compare [*glob:WINNER], and also the old MIT [Jargon File|https://jargon-file.org/archive/jargon-1.0.0.33.dos.txt].
	Note that if you refer to `ME` (or `CRETIN`), you get the [*obj:ME] global object, not the `ADVENTURER`.

obj:ME: A global object which is always in scope. Commands referring to `ME` hit this, rather than [*obj:ADVENTURER], which is a stub that moves around the map.
	Because of this, parser messages mostly refer to you as “you”, even though the [*obj:ADVENTURER]’s printed name is “cretin”.

glob:WINNER: `WINNER` is the actor in the current command. 
	`WINNER` is usually [~obj:ADVENTURER], but for a command like `COMPUTER, CINFORM` it shifts to the named NPC.
	“Winner” is just as sarcastic as “[cretin|*obj:ADVENTURER]”, but from the other side.

glob:HERE: The location of the [*glob:WINNER].

glob:LIT: Whether the current location has light. Set by calling the [rtn:LIT?] routine.

rtn:LIT?: Determine whether a given location has light. This is true if the room or anything in it has [attr:ONBIT], or if [glob:ALWAYS-LIT] is set.
	This routine is used to set the [glob:LIT] variable.

glob:ALWAYS-LIT: Whether every location in the game has light.
	The only dark rooms in *Starcross* are the yellow halls, so this flag is set when you repair the yellow lighting. See [DESCRIBE-ROOM|~src:VERBS-75].

glob:LOAD-ALLOWED: The weight limit you can carry. This is always 100.

glob:LOW-DIRECTION: Properties with this value and above are directions.
	*Starcross* [declares|~src:DUNGEON-8] `LAND` and `CROSS` as properties 22 and 23, but never uses them. So really the directions are 24 and above.

attr:ONBIT: Set for glowing objects and permanently-illuminated rooms.

attr:RLANDBIT: Set for rooms with gravity and a solid floor. The practical effect is that the disks work in such rooms.

attr:SPACEBIT: Set for rooms in outer space. You need the [obj:SPACESUIT] to survive.

attr:RAIRBIT: Set for room with air but no gravity.

attr:VILLAIN: Generally set for living beings, although they may or may not be villainous. Also the [~obj:NEST], probably so that you can assault it.
	Compare [~attr:VICBIT].
	The [~obj:ADVENTURER] has the `VILLAIN` flag, which leads to a few buggy messages. Try `HELLO ME` or `WAKE ME`, for example.

attr:VICBIT: Generally set for living beings, though not the [~obj:ADVENTURER].
	This is almost the same as [~attr:VILLAIN], but some verbs use [~attr:VILLAIN] and some `VICBIT`, with no obvious pattern.

glob:P-WON: Set if the parser successfully parsed a command. (As opposed to a blank line or an error.)
	No relation to whether the *player* has won, which is [glob:WON-FLAG].
	
glob:WON-FLAG: Set when you win the game. This affects how your [score|~rtn:V-SCORE] is displayed.

glob:LUCKY: In *Starcross*, you are always lucky.

glob:C-INTS: Indicates how much of the timer table ([*glob:C-TABLE]) is used. This counts down from `C-TABLELEN`, which is 180.

glob:C-DEMONS: Indicates how much of the timer table is used for daemons.
	The difference between daemons and timers is that timers run every turn; daemons run every *input*, even if no turn passes. But *Starcross* does not use daemons.

glob:C-TABLE: The timer table. See the “Timers” tab for a current listing.

TIMERS-LEGEND: A list of the timers running (or paused) in the timer table ([~glob:C-TABLE]). Positive numbers count down (while enabled) and call the named function after that many turns. Negative numbers are called every turn while the timer is enabled.
	This list only grows as you play; timers can be added, started, and stopped, but not removed.

rtn:GO: Set up the world at the start of the game. Start the timers. Print the banner. Set all those useful globals like [~glob:HERE] and [~glob:WINNER].
	(Note the commented-out line that sets the `I-LAMP` timer. Left over from when this code was copied from Zork!)
	`GO` also fills in the [glob:MASSES] and [glob:KNOWNS] tables, which is odd because they are both defined with their contents in place. The values this routine stores are already present. Possibly this indicates a bug in an earlier version of the ZIL compiler?

rtn:ZPROB: This function is never called.
	Every die-roll in *Starcross* uses the one-argument form of [PROB|~src:MACROS-66]. That’s compiled as an inlined `@RANDOM` opcode, not `ZPROB`.
	`ZPROB` has extra logic to decrease your chance of success if you are un-[glob:LUCKY]. But nothing in the game makes you un-[glob:LUCKY], so this is never needed.

rtn:JIGS-UP: This routine handles your demise and possible resurrection. For game endings with no second chance, see [rtn:FINISH].

rtn:FINISH: This routine displays your score and ends the game.


src:SF-2: The game is variously referred to in the source headers as “Zork SF Game” and “Interlogic SF Game”. “Zork SF” has the earlier dates (1981 alone), so that must have been how Infocom originally thought of *Starcross*.

src:DUNGEON-3: This is so closely derived from the Zork source code that the game map is still called the “DUNGEON”!

src:DUNGEON-8: The `LAND` and `CROSS` directions are carried over from Zork 2 or 3. *Starcross* does not use these. (*Zork 1* didn’t have `CROSS`, but it had `LAND` in the sense of “land the raft”.)
	*Starcross* is the first Infocom game to dispense with diagonal directions. This is probably because of the `FORE`, `AFT`, `STARBOARD`, `PORT` synonyms; an `AFTPORT` exit would be confusing. Happily the very grid-like map works in this setting.

src:EMERG-6: The comment refers to “lighting and environmental controls”, but it’s not obvious why *these* devices have been split off into their own file. All the rest of the game logic is stuffed into `actions.zil`. Perhaps the author started to split everything up into functional groups and just never got very far.

obj:GRUE-SIGN: The artifact has dark rooms; dark rooms have grues; therefore the artifact needs a source of grues. They’re willing to drop the world consistency by putting the sign in English, though.
	(Also by implying that the artifact has visited Sol system before? Nothing else in the game says that.)
	`WHAT IS A GRUE` works, by the way.

rtn:V-FROBOZZ: No command calls this verb routine, sadly. (Zork 1 and 2 had an analogous routine invoked by typing `FROBOZZ`.)

rtn:V-REPORT: The command `COMPUTER, REPORT STATUS` works and is useful in the first scene.

rtn:V-SMELL: Delightfully, if you’re wearing the [~obj:SPACESUIT], everything smells like a space suit.


glob:MASSES: The object numbers of the eight uncharted masses.

glob:KNOWNS: The object numbers of the seven charted masses.

glob:IN-ARTIFACT?: This flag is set when you enter the artifact and cleared when you leave. This determines whether you care about the state of the artifact’s atmosphere.

src:ACTIONS-60: The cranky computer must surely have been inspired by *Hitchhiker’s Guide*. (The idea of an actual collaboration with Adams was probably still a year or so off.)

src:ACTIONS-709: This is the only point where the game mentions that you’re prospecting for *quantum* black holes – that is, microscopic ones. (The manual intro also mentions it, but who reads manuals...) We’re not talking about giant star-swallowing black holes hiding in the asteroid belt.
	Stephen Hawking first hypothesized quantum black holes in the 1970s. They quickly became an SF staple. Teeny-weeny ones would evaporate instantly, but slightly less tiny “primordial” holes left over from the Big Bang might survive.

obj:SPACESUIT: The suit’s oxygen tank has no timer or limit. Everybody plays as if it’s a precious resource, but it’s not!
	(But you can’t use this fact to survive after the artifact’s atmosphere goes bad. See [rtn:I-BAD-AIR].)

obj:SAFETY-HOOK: An Infocom ZIL manual from 1982 mentions:
	“(Verb synonyms) must be used with great caution if they are also another part of speech.  This problem occurred in STARCROSS with the word HOOK, which was made a synonym of TIE.  Unfortunately, HOOK is also a noun in STARCROSS.  The results were peculiar.  Speak to Dave (Lebling) or Marc (Blank) if a problem like this arises.”


rtn:TENTACLE-APPEARS: This routine sneakily starts up the artifact’s general timers ([rtn:I-MOUSE] and [rtn:I-BAD-AIR]). We don’t want to run down the atmosphere timer while the player figures out how to control their ship.


rtn:I-BAD-AIR: This timer handles the slow degradation of the artifact’s atmosphere.
	If the air runs out completely while you are wearing the [obj:SPACESUIT], the power goes out instead – sorry! If you were outside the artifact, the shutdown politely waits for you to return.
	
rtn:I-POISON-AIR: This timer handles the replacement of the artifact’s atmosphere if you select the wrong option in the [~obj:REPAIR-ROOM].
	As with [rtn:I-BAD-AIR], wearing the [obj:SPACESUIT] will not save you.
	
rtn:I-FRESH-AIR: This timer handles the refreshing of the artifact’s atmosphere if you select the right option in the [~obj:REPAIR-ROOM].


rtn:I-MOUSE: This timer controls the [~obj:MOUSE]. It runs every other turn after you dock ([rtn:TENTACLE-APPEARS]). The plan in a nutshell:
	It tries to pick up nearby objects ([~rtn:ROB]).
	If it’s in the [~obj:GARAGE], it deposits its load in the [~obj:TRASH-BIN], and then (40% chance) returns to [glob:MOUSE-LOC] through its sneaky [~obj:MOUSE-HOLE].
	If it’s anywhere else, it has a 15% chance of going to the [~obj:GARAGE] and setting [glob:MOUSE-LOC]. Otherwise, it proceeds on its rounds via [rtn:MOVE-MOUSE] and does an additional [~rtn:ROB] for good measure.

src:ACTIONS-974: The discs have to be outside the container so that you can teleport properly.
	If the [~obj:MOUSE] doesn’t leave the [~obj:GARAGE] next turn, it will pick the disks up and immediately drop them. [rtn:I-MOUSE] avoids printing the “picks up some refuse” while in the [~obj:GARAGE], so the player won’t notice this.

glob:SEEN-MOUSE?: Whether you’ve seen the mouse before. The first time it appears, you are treated to a long description ([~glob:LONG-MOUSE]) by way of introduction.

rtn:MOVE-MOUSE: Move the [~obj:MOUSE] on its regular random walk through the artifact. (Going to and from the [~obj:GARAGE] is handled by [rtn:I-MOUSE].)
	It iterates through the properties of the mouse’s location. ([Direction properties|~src:DUNGEON-8] are listed first.) The first valid exit found is stored in `.D`; further valid exits have a 50% chance of replacing `.D`. When the loop is out of directions, if `.D` is set, the mouse moves there. (Except that [~obj:MAZE] and [~obj:UP-A-TREE] are off-limits.)
	The result is a fairly random exit selection, although it’s biased towards later directions: `SOUTH` is more likely than `NORTH`, etc.
	(This is an unusually LISP-y function. It took me several tries to work out how it worked.)

# for P in properties:
#   T = H.&P
#   L = H.#P
#   if T represents a valid exit:
#     if (not D) or 50% chance:
#       D = the T exit destination
# if D:
#   move mouse to D (except MAZE or UP-A-TREE)

glob:MOUSE-LOC: The room from which the [~obj:MOUSE] entered the [~obj:GARAGE], and to which it will return.

glob:GARAGED?: Set for one turn (only) after the [~obj:MOUSE] enters the [~obj:GARAGE].


src:ACTIONS-2169: This “Lose, lose!” message seems to cover a branch that cannot occur ([~glob:P-ADJECTIVE] is neither zero nor non-zero). Possibly this was needed to cover a compiler bug?
	Interestingly, the compiled file is missing the string “Lose, lose!” – it’s just got a lone “!” Same compiler bug? Or was the source modified after the last compile?

obj:LADDER: No `LADDER` object is defined in the source! But [~obj:BLUE-THREE] and [~obj:YELLOW-THREE] refer to it (in their `GLOBAL` properties.) Because of this, the compiler generated an anonymous object with no properties. It cannot be referred to and has no effect in the game.
	Those rooms were very likely intended to refer to the [~obj:STAIRS] scenery object instead. (It has `LADDER` as a synonym.)

src:DUNGEON-984: The [obj:LADDER] scenery reference should probably be to [~obj:STAIRS] instead.

src:DUNGEON-1051: The [obj:LADDER] scenery reference should probably be to [~obj:STAIRS] instead.

src:ACTIONS-3199: I always wanted to be able to put *any* rod into the gun, and thus produce a “giant blast of red rays” or “black rays” or whatever color I wanted. Sadly the game does not support it.

src:ACTIONS-2127: Pluto was still a planet when *Starcross* was written.
	The first time I faced this puzzle, I didn’t catch on that the first bump was the Sun. I pressed the `FOURTH BUMP` because Mars was the nearest planet – it was even mentioned on the mass chart! Luckily my mistakes cancelled out.

src:ACTIONS-1586: The first thing I ever tried with the disks was putting one on top of the other. They exploded, and I decided they must be a two-part explosive! I spent several days trying to solve puzzles by blowing things up before I realized my mistake.

src:ACTIONS-3767: Once you repair the lights, there are no dark rooms in the game. (See [glob:ALWAYS-LIT].) I always thought it was a bit unfair that you could be eaten by grues at that point.
